A slight oversimplification of the rules is that in, in the US, it is illeg=
al for brokers to charge clients money directly for investment research, wh=
ile in the EU it is=C2=A0illegal=C2=A0for brokers=C2=A0not=C2=A0to charge c=
lients money directly for investment research. In the US, brokers provide r=
esearch for =E2=80=9Cfree,=E2=80=9D and clients compensate them for the res=
earch by doing trades with them and paying commissions for the trades. The =
EU dislikes the  potential conflicts of interest in that model,
  [7]
 so in the 2018 Markets in Financial Instruments Directive it=C2=A0banned=
=C2=A0it: Clients have to pay for research explicitly. In the US, though, c=
harging people for research might make you an =E2=80=9Cinvestment adviser,=
=E2=80=9D requiring separate registration with the Securities and Exchange =
Commission and creating awkward new fiduciary obligations.
For the last five years the SEC has sort of waived this conflict, telling U=
S=C2=A0brokers that they can comply with Mifid (by charging European client=
s directly for research) without registering as investment advisers. But no=
w that is ending. The  Financial Times reports:

After July 3, US broker-dealers are set to lose the protection of a five-ye=
ar =E2=80=9Cno action=E2=80=9D letter from the Securities and Exchange Comm=
ission that covered them against having to register as investment advisers.=
 =E2=80=A6
Without that protection they face a choice of registering, moving research =
teams into already registered affiliates, or potentially cutting off client=
s bound by Mifid regulations from research produced in the US.
=E2=80=9CBanks are talking to each other and to their clients. It=E2=80=99s=
 already causing disruption,=E2=80=9D said one person involved in the behin=
d-the-scenes discussions. =E2=80=A6
Banks have resisted investment adviser status because it would restrict the=
m from some activities including principal trading, and could hinder their =
ability to offer bespoke research, according to people with experience of t=
he rules. The costs and complications of reorganising to register would dep=
end on each bank=E2=80=99s individual arrangements, but were not insurmount=
able, they added.

It is a strange little conflict? One way to read the situation is that the =
SEC doesn=E2=80=99t mind forcing brokers to register their research arms as=
 investment advisers with fiduciary duties to the research customers.=C2=A0=
The SEC has historically been a little suspicious of sell-side investment r=
esearch, and the main suspicion is=C2=A0that sometimes research analysts se=
em to  recommend stocks for reasons other than that they think the stocks w=
ill go up. (To  maintain corporate access, for instance, or historically to=
  win investment banking business.) It would be hard for the SEC to write n=
ew rules saying that research analysts are fiduciaries for the people who r=
ead their reports, but it=E2=80=99s possible that European regulators have =
done that work for the SEC.

